1.İntroduction
My research question is "İs total amount of debit and credit card expenditure related to
consumer price index, unemployement rate and weighted average interest rates for banks
loans?" The reason that I choose this topic is nowadays most of the time people use debit or
credit cards instead of cashes. The idea behind this question is try to figure out which factors
can affect percentage of credit or debit card usage. Without any analysis, first of all, I guess
that people may be more likely to use cards when the unemployment rate increases. Because
they need to maintain some basic needs. In addition, when the interest rate increases, people
can decrease their habit of using cards. Maybe, they consider that usage of cards are not that
much profitable at this point. Another guess is that people will increase their card usage due to
the price index increase. Due to the price increases, they may not be able to pay cash to buy
some products, so there might be a tendency to use cards.
2. Analysis Steps
Firstly, I decided of my data sets and dependent statistics. Each of my data set comes from
different categories and their frequency is monthly. Then I downloaded these data sets from
https://evds2.tcmb.gov.tr/ as an Excell file.
After that I started to use Rstudio and I install the packages which I would have need in the
analysis.
install.packages("data.table")
library(data.table)
install.packages("xlsx")
install.packages("zoo")
install.packages("xts")
install.packages("ggpubr")
library(zoo)
library(xts)
library(readxl)
library(ggpubr)
Then, read the Excel files by using the following codes.
data <- read_excel("C:/Users/LENOVO/Desktop/EVDS.xlsx")
View(data)
The statistics that I had include 37 months of observations of my variables. So I created
sequences of dates in order to obtain time series object. I created xts object that contains all
data.
dates<- seq(from=as.Date("2016-10-01"),to=as.Date("2019-10-31"),by="months")
genelxts<-xts(x=data[1:37,],order.by=dates)
The statistic that I wanted to interpret the relationsahip with other variables is Amount of
credit and debit card expenditure. I created another time series object for this statistics.
card_exp <- data[1:37,2]
cardxts<- xts(x=card_exp,order.by=dates)
storage.mode(cardxts) <- "numeric"
str(cardxts)
I wanted to see the relationships with Card expenditure with three variables. First of them is
average interest for banks loans. I created xts object for this variable
loan_interest<- data[1:37,3]
loanxts<- xts(x=loan_interest,order.by=dates) #xts object for interest rates of loans
storage.mode(loanxts)<- "numeric"
The second variable is consumer price index. So I created another xts object for consumer
price index.
price_index <- data[1:37,4]
pricexts <- xts(x=price_index,order.by=dates) #xts object for price indexes
storage.mode(pricexts)<- "numeric"
The third one is unemployemt rate. I created another xts object for it.
unemp_rate <-data[1:37,5]
unempxts <- xts(x=unemp_rate,order.by=dates) #xts object for unemployement rates
storage.mode(unempxts)<- "numeric"
I have created 5 xts object. As I mentioned the first one is combination of all xts objects.Then
I plot the 4 of my xts object to visualize.
plot(cardxts)
plot(loanxts)
plot(pricexts)
plot(unempxts)
Then I merge the other xts objects with my card expenditure xts object
merge(cardxts,loanxts)
merge(cardxts,pricexts)
merge(cardxts,unempxts)
I plot my dependent variable card expenditure xts object with other xts object in order to
visiualize their relationship.
qqplot(loanxts,cardxts) #qqplots of cardxts against other xts objects
qqplot(pricexts,cardxts)
qqplot(unempxts,cardxts)
I applied correlation test to find the correlation coefficient and by using it analysize the
relationship of card expenditure with other variables.
cor1 <- cor.test(cardxts, loanxts, method = "pearson") #correlation measurments between
cardxts and other xts objects
cor2 <- cor.test(cardxts, pricexts, method = "pearson")
cor3 <- cor.test(cardxts, unempxts, method = "pearson")
Finally I want to check the periodicity of my xts object.
periodicity(cardxts)
periodicity(loanxts)
periodicity(pricexts)
periodicity(unempxts)
3.İnterpratation of Results and Plots
Tables shows the correlation relationship between card expenditure and other variables. We
can see that estimation of correlation coefficient. Table 1 calculate correlation between card
expenditure and interest rate of a loan. The estimate of correlation coefficient is 0.55 so we
can say that there is moderate relationship between these variables. Table 2 calculate
correlation between card expenditure and price index . Estimate of 0.73 says that these
variables have pretty good relationship. Table 3 calculate the correlation between card
expenditure and unemployement rate. Estimate 0,26 refers that there is weak relationship
between these variables.
At first sight it is hard to obtain reasonable rasults just looking the 37 months of
observations.But visualization gives me some hints. When I looked at the figure 1 which is
refers to debit and credit card expenditure it is hard to say that it has a steady behavior
between consecutive points.But instead of monthly observations if we had use 2 or 3 monhtly
freaquency there would be an increasing trend overall. As it seem to be there are sharp
increases and decreases between consecutive months.It also reaches the lowest value in
January 2017 and it reaches the highest value in August 2020 .
At figure 2 which refers to interest rate of loans there is a slow increase in until April 2018,
but with a rapid increase after April 2018, it reaches the maximum point in October 2018.
From September 2018 to October 2018 we observe an increase in figure 1 too.
At figure 3 which refers price index there is obviously an increasing trend. Only after October
2018 there is a pretty small decreas for 2 months then again we observe increasing trend. We
also observed an increase from September 2018 to October 2018 in Figure 1, which may be
a similarity.
Figure 4 which refers to unemployement rate reaches the lowest value in april 2018 and the
highest value in january 2019.There is an increase from September 2018 to October 2018 as
weel as figure 1
In general, we can say that there was an increase in Figure 1,Figure 2, Figure 3 and Figure 4
from April 2018 to October 2018. Perhaps this may be a clue that card expenditure ,Figure1,
was affected by other variables in that period.
At figure 5 there is a plot card expenditure against interest of loans. Figure 5
says there may be a relatively linear relationship
At figure 6 there is a plot card expenditure against price index.This figure is the one that more
likely indicate almost linear relationship between card expenditure and price index.
At figure 7 there is a plot card expenditure against unepmloyement rate . Although the figure
7 tells us there may be a linear relationship, we know from correlation coefficient that this
relationship is weak

5.Conculusion
As a result, we can say that the variable that affects card spending the most is the price index.
In addition, the interest rate of loans affects card spending. The unemployment rate, on the
other hand, has little effect on card spending. It may be more efficient to use another variable
instead of it.

install.packages("data.table")
library(data.table)
install.packages("xlsx")
install.packages("zoo")
install.packages("xts")
install.packages("ggpubr")
library(zoo)
library(xts)
library(readxl)
library(ggpubr)
data <- read_excel("C:/Users/LENOVO/Desktop/EVDS.xlsx")
View(data)
dates<- seq(from=as.Date("2016-10-01"),to=as.Date("2019-10-31"),by="months")
genelxts<-xts(x=data[1:37,],order.by=dates)
card_exp <- data[1:37,2]
cardxts<- xts(x=card_exp,order.by=dates) #xts object for card usage
storage.mode(cardxts) <- "numeric"
str(cardxts)
loan_interest<- data[1:37,3]
loanxts<- xts(x=loan_interest,order.by=dates) #xts object for interest rates of loans
storage.mode(loanxts)<- "numeric"
price_index <- data[1:37,4]
pricexts <- xts(x=price_index,order.by=dates) #xts object for price indexes
storage.mode(pricexts)<- "numeric"
unemp_rate <-data[1:37,5]
unempxts <- xts(x=unemp_rate,order.by=dates) #xts object for unemployement rates
storage.mode(unempxts)<- "numeric"
plot(cardxts) #plot the 4 xts objects
plot(loanxts)
plot(pricexts)
plot(unempxts)
merge(cardxts,loanxts) #compare cardxts wit the other xts object
merge(cardxts,pricexts)
merge(cardxts,unempxts)
qqplot(loanxts,cardxts) #qqplots of cardxts against other xts objects
qqplot(pricexts,cardxts)
qqplot(unempxts,cardxts)
cor1 <- cor.test(cardxts, loanxts, method = "pearson") #correlation measurments between
cardxts and other xts objects
cor2 <- cor.test(cardxts, pricexts, method = "pearson")
cor3 <- cor.test(cardxts, unempxts, method = "pearson")
periodicity(cardxts) #periodicity calculations of xts objects (check if they are monthly)
periodicity(loanxts)
periodicity(pricexts)
periodicity(unempxts)
